 programs are cut, Madriz points out, those for more prisons and police are on the increase. She also illustrates how media images of victims—"good" victims aren't culpable, "bad" victims invite trouble—and a tough political stance toward criminals are linked to a general climate of economic uncertainty and conservatism.Madriz argues that fear itself is a strong element in keeping women in subservient and self-limiting social positions. "Policing" themselves, they construct a restricted world that leads to positions of even greater subordination: Being a woman means being vulnerable. Considering the enormous attention given to crime today, including victims' rights and use of public funds, Madriz's informative study is especially timely.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aFear of crimezUnited States. 0aWomenxCrimes againstzUnited States. 0aWomenzUnited StatesxAttitudes. 0aWomenzUnited StatesxPsychology. 0aWomenzUnited StateszUnited StatesxAttitudes. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh  aabuse.  aanxiety.  abad victims.  aconservative politics.  acrime.  acriminal justice.  acriminology.  aculpability.  adanger.  afear of crime.  afear.  afemale victims.  afeminism.  afeminist theory.  agender hierarchy.  agender studies.  agender.  agood victims.  alaw and order.  alegal system.  amedia.  anonfiction.  apatriarchy.  apotential victim.  apoverty.  arisk management.  asocial justice.  asocial programs.  asocial science.  asubservience.  athreat perception.  athreat.  avictims rights.  avictims.  aviolence against women.  avulnerability.  awomen.  awomens issues.  awomens studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052020855